><div class="inset"><div class="article__byline" data-lpos="author-top"><span>By </span><span class="article__author"><span><span class="article__author-name">Curtis Rush</span></span><span><span class="article__author-credit">Police Reporter</span></span></span></div><div class="article__published-date">Thu., May 31, 2012</div></div><div class="clearfix share-toolbar " data-lpos="share-toolbar"><div class="gutter-icon"><i class="staricon staricon-share "></i></div><div class="share-toolbar__body"><div class="clearfix sticky-replace sticky-replace--inset" data-sticky-replace="true"><div class="sticky-replace__body"><ul class="share-toolbar__primary clearfix"><li><a title="Share on Facebook"><i class="staricon staricon-facebook "></i></a></li><li><a title="Share on Twitter"><i class="staricon staricon-twitter "></i></a></li><li><a title="Share with email"><i class="staricon staricon-email-outlined "></i></a></li><li><a title="More share options" class="share-toolbar-more"><i class="staricon staricon-more-dots "></i></a></li></ul></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="article-body-items" data-lpos="article-body"><div class="trackContent-0"><p>When you pay a restaurant bill at your table using a point-of-sale machine, are you sure it&rsquo;s legit?</p><p>In the past three months, Toronto and Peel police have discovered many that aren&rsquo;t.</p></div><div class="hero blur_effect"><figure class="image hideRegistration"><div class="image__body"><img src="https://images.thestar.com/7TiprX-C3-69znh5rAKjVTBC8F0=/1200x557/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg" srcSet="https://images.thestar.com/7TiprX-C3-69znh5rAKjVTBC8F0=/1200x557/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 1200w,https://images.thestar.com/g_0XKoYNuEgwdRjR-ed9_KaB7Cg=/1086x504/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 1086w,https://images.thestar.com/P7bZMhwIdGwxF9vcpFQXuCi754E=/968x449/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 968w,https://images.thestar.com/YJUkpxBNobay2TTxwJGRU-mdfuY=/850x395/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 850w,https://images.thestar.com/OI9BRJ6xN2EWTGHKezHJv5cicDQ=/650x302/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 650w,https://images.thestar.com/tgZAtt43IhRoKYDPTYX6cqCk-i0=/605x281/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 605w,https://images.thestar.com/E-m8HQqhCWlz9kNC7timGSJaG4I=/480x223/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 480w,https://images.thestar.com/blg40UQzSG7HVB_7kpVM9_3VHa4=/400x186/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 400w,https://images.thestar.com/DGC7rKqdn9FA3JYLr_N0opwOEJk=/320x149/smart/filters:cb(2700061000)/https://www.thestar.com/content/dam/thestar/news/crime/2012/05/31/portable_credit_card_terminals_used_in_fraud/pointofsale.jpeg 320w" alt="Police display the back of a point-of-sale terminal to show it has been tampered with."/></div><figcaption>Police display the back of a point-of-sale terminal to show it has been tampered with.<span class="image__credit">Â Â (<span class="image__credit__source">CURTIS RUSH<span> / </span>TORONTO STAR</span>)</span></figcaption></figure></div><div><div><div class="alpha alpha--big-box show-for-medium-up hideRegistration"></div></div></div><div class="trackContent-3 blur_effect hideRegistration"><p>In what is the latest financial fraud, crooks are using distraction techniques to replace merchants&rsquo; machines with their own, police say.</p><p>At the end of the day, they create another distraction to pull the switch again.</p><p>Using information inputted by customers, including PIN data, the criminals are reproducing credit cards at an alarming rate.</p></div><div class="show-for-small-only alpha__big-box  hideRegistration"><div class="article-continued"><div class="article-continued__heading">Article Continued Below</div></div><div class="alpha__big-box__body"><div class="big-box"></div></div></div><div class="trackContent-5 blur_effect hideRegistration"><p>Merchants must be wary this is going on and train their staff, police told reporters Thursday.</p><p>One way to tell if a machine is fraudulent is if a credit card can be pushed in so far that you can&rsquo;t easily put your thumb on the end of it.</p><p>That might indicate the machine is reading the card&rsquo;s magnetic stripe and recording your data.</p><p>&ldquo;The only data that is capable of being compromised to our knowledge is the data associated to magnetic strips,&rdquo; said Det. Ian Nichol. &ldquo;The industry is taking steps to minimize this.&rdquo;</p><p>At some point, all point-of-sale terminals will be switched over to accept only chip cards, police say.</p></div><div id="fsk_splitbox"></div><div class="trackContent-8 blur_effect hideRegistration"><p>Transactions at many smaller retail locations still use only magnetic stripe technology.</p><p>Nichol advises retailers to check their terminals at the beginning, middle and end of a shift and ensure the number on the machine is the same.</p></div><div class="show-for-small-only alpha__big-box  hideRegistration"><div class="article-continued"><div class="article-continued__heading">Article Continued Below</div></div><div class="alpha__big-box__body"><div class="big-box"></div></div></div><div class="trackContent-10 blur_effect hideRegistration"><p>The crime has turned up in Toronto, Peel and Montreal, police say.</p><p>A few weeks ago, a store owner in a Toronto food court alerted police to suspicious activity with his point-of-sale machine.</p><p>The Financial Crimes Unit conducted surveillance and arrested a man in the act, police say.</p><p>Staff Insp. Bryce Evans, with the Financial Crimes Unit, said he believes money gained from financial crime is likely going to terrorist or other criminal organizations outside the country.</p><p>In many such cases, he said, arrests are made in scrubby houses or apartments, not the luxurious homes of people expected to be profiting alone from the crime.</p><p>Although perceived as a victimless crime because the banks are on the hook for losses, police argue this fraud costs everyone because financial institutions must spend money on high security.</p><p>In another disturbing trend, police say financial crime has now surpassed drugs in value as the leading crime in Canada.</p><p>Evans said a recent survey found people are more concerned about financial crime than any other.</p></div><div class="article-trust-bar clearfix hideRegistration" data-lpos="article-trust-bar"><ul><li class="report-error"><a><i class="staricon staricon-error-reporting "></i>Report an error</a></li><li class="journalistic-standards"><span><span><a href="/about/statementofprinciples.html"><i class="staricon staricon-journalistic-standards "></i>Journalistic Standards</a></span></span></li><li class="about-the"><span><span><a href="/about/aboutus.html"><i class="staricon staricon-trust-icon "></i>About <em>The Star</em></a></span></span></li></ul></div><div class="trackContentHidden blur_effect hideRegistration"></div><div class="show-for-small-only banner-content hideRegistration" data-lpos="newsletter-signup"><div class="row"><div class="banner-inner-content"><div class="banner-inner-content__left side-box__title title-color-headlines"><div class="about-text">TOP STORIES, DELIVERED TO YOUR INBOX.</div></div><div class="banner-inner-content__right"><div class="side-box__subline"><span class="subline-icon-color-headlines">NEW NEWSLETTER</span><span>HEADLINES</span></div><div class="side-box__button"><span><span><a href="/emails.html">SIGN UP</a></span></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></article><div class="partner-contents  hideRegistration"><div class="row"><div class="partner-contents__body"><h3 class="partner-contents__heading">More from The Star &amp; Partners</h3><ul class="small-block-grid-2 medium-block-grid-4 large-block-grid-4"><li class="partner-content"></li><li class="partner-content"></li><li class="partner-content show-for-medium-up"></li><li class="partner-content show-for-medium-up"></li></ul></div></div></div><div><div><div><div class="nested-aggregate-spacer container-gutters hideRegistration"></div><div class="aggregation clearfix hideRegistration"><div><div><section class="simple container-aggregation container-gutters" data-lpos="loading"><div class="container-aggregation__overset"></div><div class="section-header clearfix full-bleed"><div class="section-header__gutter loading"></div><div class="clearfix sticky-replace sticky-replace--narrow" data-sticky-replace="true"><div class="sticky-replace__body"><h2 class="no-wrap"><span><span>LOADING</span></span></h2></div></div></div><div class="container-aggregation__body loading"><div class="simple__top clearfix"><div class="row"><div class="columns"><ul class="small-block-grid-1 medium-block-grid-1 large-block-grid-1"><li><div class="story small-story--feature medium-story--small-feature large-story--small-feature story__placeholder"><div class="story__image"><div class="img-block">Â </div><